# Game Theory: Strategic Upset Selection

Using the expected value framework from the document:

$$EV = P \times V \times (1 - O)$$

where $P$ = probability of upset, $V$ = point value of the round, $O$ = fraction of brackets selecting the upset.

For this analysis we approximate ownership using seed-based priors (popular upsets like 12-over-5 have ~50% ownership; unlikely ones are much lower).

```{r upset-ev}
# Round of 64 upset opportunities
round_points <- c(`Round of 64` = 1, `Round of 32` = 2, `Sweet 16` = 4,
                  `Elite Eight` = 8, `Final Four` = 16, Championship = 32)

# Ownership prior by seed of lower seed winning
ownership_prior <- c(`16`=0.02, `15`=0.05, `14`=0.10, `13`=0.15,
                     `12`=0.48, `11`=0.45, `10`=0.35, `9`=0.45)

r64_pairs_all <- do.call(c, lapply(regions, function(r) {
  get_round64_pairs(teams %>% filter(region == r) %>% arrange(slot))
}))

ev_rows <- lapply(r64_pairs_all, function(p) {
  fav   <- p[1]; dog <- p[2]
  p_upset <- 1 - win_prob(em_vec[fav], em_vec[dog])
  dog_seed <- teams$seed[teams$team == dog]
  own <- ownership_prior[as.character(dog_seed)]
  if (is.na(own)) own <- 0.20
  ev <- round(p_upset * 1 * (1 - own), 3)
  tibble(Favorite = fav, Underdog = dog,
         `P(Upset)` = round(p_upset, 3),
         `Ownership (est.)` = own,
         `EV (Round of 64)` = ev)
}) %>% bind_rows() %>% arrange(desc(`EV (Round of 64)`))

ev_rows %>%
  head(15) %>%
  kable(caption = "Top 15 Round of 64 Upset Opportunities by Expected Value") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width = FALSE)
```

